Mar 4 2006 	Good hotel at a great location parts of the hotel premise need renovation	Stayed here from 2/15-2/20 then again from 2/23-2/27. It is an older hotel but has gone under extensive renovation recently. Some rooms have the traditional beautiful Chinese garden setting. The location is unbeatable - it is right on Jianguomen Street and close to the World Trade Center, a major shopping area as well as the subway (right in front of the hotel). Very popular hotel for foreign guests.I got different rooms during my stay - be sure to request a room in Building A as all rooms on this side were recently furbished and nicely decorated (equipped with mini-bar, tea/coffee station and a nice bathroom). Many rooms in Building B are old and dingy looking, I was put in a room on Building B side for one night and had to request the room change the following morning due to its filthiness and noise. Other than this minor problem, I had a very pleasant stay. Hotel staff is professional, good room services, wonderful selection of breakfast and free in-room broadband internet access. There are many newer hotels on Jianguo Men Street/Dong Chang An Street but this one seems like it's always one of the favorite hotel for foreign guests. Wouldn't mind coming back again.	
Dec 3 2005	Handy and Hospitable	We stayed at this hotel for five nights and had a very pleasant experience. The hotel is rated four-star according to the local system and it certainly lived up to Western four-star standards. Our room was not huge but nicely appointed with a good sized bathroom. The bed was a comfortable king-size and the TV provided local and international channels including BBC, CNN, French, German and Italian, as well as ESPN and Star Sports. Bottled water was provided to our room each day. Staff were very freindly and helpful and spoke enough English for simple conversations and requests. Staff at reception and in the restaurant spoke more English than others. For more complicated issues, such as the location of an ATM, we found hand gestures got the message across. The entrance to the hotel was being refurbished for the 2008 Olympics but this had no effect on our stay and management provided a 50 yuan voucher for use in the hotel restaurants to compensate for any inconvenience. The hotel is located very conveniently on the main road which runs east-west through Beijing past Tiananmen Square and the Forbidden City. Under the building next door is a subway station only four stops from Tiananmen. The only drawback was the lack of places to eat in the district. We found a noodle restaurant and an Indian/Thai resturant but that was about it. The hotel itself has several restaurants including an excellent Chinese.	
